explainerText: The fire north of Wye River was contained on Christmas morning, before the fire broke containment lines.
Wind pushed the fire towards the coast, and most people evacuated Wye River and Separation Creek.
The wind meant the fire burned hot and travelled quickly in dryer-than-usual conditions.
A small number of fire fighters and volunteers from the community stayed behind to help others evacuate and fight the fire.
Fire fighters continued their work into the night, when the helicopters could not.

The fire destroyed 116 houses but no lives were lost, and the community's key buildings were saved.
